post_text:
Athletes and Parent/Guardians of Athletes
To participate in Sussex Academy athletics please note the following;
DIAA has a new physical form that is available on Sussexacademysports.com (on left under list of teams, (DIAA Physical Forms) and on our school website (General Info – Forms – about half way down, DIAA 2020-21 Preparticipation Physical Form Packet final rv 7-16-20 )
All 9th grade students, 6th grade students, out of state transfer students, and first time participants in sports must submit a completed DIAA form dated after 4/1/2020 to participate.
Other returning athletes (with a 19-20 DIAA physical form on file) will have to submit a new physical (dated after 4/1/20) before the start of the winter season. To participate in fall athletics they will have to submit Pg. 3 (Health History) and Pg. 5 (Medical card). When completing Pg. 3 (Health history) make sure to only answer “Yes” if there are new issues since you were last cleared for participation last year.
Questions – contact athletic director Steve Bastianelli steve.bastianelli@saas.k12.de.us

post_text:
Dr. Douglas Newton and Varsity Tutors.
He is realistic, optimistic, and compassionate.
He talks about:

1) What behaviors can parents from elementary school children expect?
2) What is the impact of COVID?
3) What are some solutions?

He reassures parents that regression is typical in these atypical times, and while it might not be welcome, it is not uncommon. He talks about the Three A’s of Anxiety and understanding the F’s of anxiety.

He also discusses the fact that kids are resilient; talks about what parents should do if they suspect that behaviors are not a normal reaction to an abnormal situation or are indications of more significant problems; talks about screen time, - amount, impact, type, and supervision.

Hope you find this helpful.

Sussex Academy’s Men’s and Women’s Soccer Spirit Wear

The spirit wear store is now open, and will remain open until July 31st at noon. We have added new items, and we are opening early so that you can have your gear in September.

Proceeds from the apparel purchases support our soccer team boosters.

Tips for ordering from the online store:

· Visit the online store: https://stores.inksoft.com/sussex_academy_menswomens_socce/shop/home
· Click on “Sign In” (upper right hand corner) and then “Create Account”. Fill in the information (email, name, password).
· Select the items you would like to order (please make sure to view all of the images with each piece--some have extra features, for example, “Seahawks” on the sleeve, logo on the back, etc.).
· Add items to your cart and then checkout; you can pay for your items online in the store.

post_text:
4th Annual High School Athletic Awards Ceremony
Tuesday, June 2 at 6pm

Due to the state guidelines on gatherings, this year’s ceremony will be held as a zoom event. All athletes, relatives, fans, and supporters of the Seahawk's athletic teams are welcome to join our broadcast. The ceremony will consist of a recap of the 2019-20 athletic seasons and the awarding of many honors. Some of these honors include; MVP for each varsity team, Scholar-Athlete award, Spirit award, Sportsmanship award, and Most Outstanding Athlete award. Those who earned All Conference and All State honors will be recognized and 4 year as well as several 5 year letter winners in a sport will be honored. There will be student-athlete speakers to welcome and conclude the ceremony. We hope that you will join us as we celebrate another fine year of Seahawk athletics. Information on joining the ceremony will be posted on our school website, our sports website, and texted or emailed to all team members. This information will hopefully be posted by Sunday 5/31.

Bella Kwan, we are so proud of you!
The Delaware Women’s Alliance for Sports and Fitness, Inc. (DWASF) is pleased to award you a Dr. Michael J. Axe/Dr. Jeremie Axe/First State Orthopedics College Scholarship of $500. There are two awards of this type given every year, one for northern Delaware and one for southern Delaware. You were selected as the 2020 Southern Delaware recipient of this award. The scholarship committee selected you in recognition of your outstanding achievements in the state of Delaware as a high school female athlete and scholar who will graduate in 2020 and will be pursuing a college career this fall.

Happy Earth Day! Today’s challenge is for you to do a trash clean-up. Many of our roadsides this time of year are unfortunately littered with trash. Head out for a walk with a trash bag, enjoy the sunshine, and help the earth at the same time. Share a picture of what you collected with us. Thanks for doing your part!

EDIT: For those participating in today's challenge-we encourage use of gloves, masks, social distancing, and washing your hands immediately after you dispose of your trash collection. Your health and safety are SA's primary concern.

It’s a challenge between all the grades and includes teachers too. We’ll be tallying daily participation. Simply accept the challenge and then post a picture of what you did. It’s easy and fun and a great way to celebrate Earth Day from home.

Today’s challenge is to create a recycled or repurposed item that you can wear, decorate with, or use in some way. Get creative and show us what you’ve done.

post_text: This message is from Sussex Academy with an update on our upcoming schedule. Friday evening, Governor Carney declared that all public schools in Delaware will close for a period of two weeks, from Monday, March 16 through Friday, March 27. Faculty and staff at Sussex Academy have developed a plan to provide continuous instruction through online learning and will be spending Monday, March 16 preparing course assignments. Monday will be considered a day off for students. Students should plan to begin accessing online assignments on Tuesday, March 17. We will send a message to students on Monday which will include a schedule for this week and directions for students to access online learning assignments.

post_text: On Friday, SA students attended the Youth Environmental Summit in Dover. There were more than 250 students from 23 schools in Delaware who came together to learn about environmental issues facing our state and nation. Princess was a lighting speaker delivering a quick address about the importance of educating migrant communities about environmental issues. Adelle spoke to the group about the impacts of climate change in our area. Students generated action plans and networked with students from other schools. The summit was entirely student planned and student led. Governor Carney and Senator Carper were both in attendance and spoke to students about the vital role that they play in enacting change in our world.
